Exploring Movie Popularity and Revenue¶

We will be exploring the movie dataset from The Movie Database (TMDB), provided on Kaggle (https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/tmdb/tmdb-movie-metadata). The dataset is in a csv, with "," delimeters. It contains the columns: id, imdb_id, popularity, budget, revenue, original_title, cast, homepage, director, tagline, overview, runtime, genres, production_companies, release_date, vote_count, vote_average, release_year, budget_adj, revenue_adj. Some columns do have "|" delimeters.

Examples of interesting questions that could be answered with this data:

  • Are movies with higher budgets more popular?
  • Do more popular movies have higher revenue?
  • Do movies with higher budgets have higher revenue?
  • Do certain directors have higher budgets?
  • Do certain directors influence revenue?
  • Is there a correlation between directors and movie popularity?
  • Are certain genres more popular than others?
  • Do certain genres earn more revenue than others?
  • Do certain times of year influence popularity?
  • Which years have the most popular movies?
  • Do certain actors influence popularity?
  • Do certain actors influence revenue?
  • Are runtime and popularity correlated?

The questions we're going to explore:

  • Are movies with higher budgets more popular?
  • Do more popular movies have higher revenue?
  • Do movies with higher budgets have higher revenue?
  • Do certain directors have higher budgets?
  • Do certain directors influence revenue?
  • Is there a correlation between directors and movie popularity?
  • Are runtime and popularity correlated?

Data Cleaning¶

Tasks:

  • Drop unnecessary columns.
  • Check data types - do any need to be changed?
  • Fill or drop NULL values.
  • Check for duplicates, drop if present.

Let's take another look at the questions we want to explore to decide which columns we can safely remove.

The questions we're going to explore:

  • Are movies with higher budgets more popular?
  • Do more popular movies have higher revenue?
  • Do movies with higher budgets have higher revenue?
  • Do certain directors have higher budgets?
  • Do certain directors influence revenue?
  • Is there a correlation between directors and movie popularity?
  • Are runtime and popularity correlated?

To answer these questions, we only need to keep id, popularity, budget, revenue, original_title, director, runtime, vote_count, vote_average, budget_adj, and revenue adj. The difference between the budget and revenue columns vs. the budget_adj and revenue_adj is that the adjusted columns account for inflation. We'll explore with both.

In [102]:
df_movies.drop(['imdb_id','cast','homepage','tagline','keywords','overview', 'genres','production_companies', 'release_date','vote_count','vote_average','release_year'], axis=1, inplace=True)

Function to return averages¶

This function will be used for further Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA). It returns the mean and median of a specific column.

In [117]:
#Defines a function to get the averages of a column (col), returns the mean and median.
def averages(col):
    avgs_mean = df_movies_clean[col].mean()
    avgs_median = df_movies_clean[col].median()
    
    
    return avgs_mean, avgs_median
In [118]:
#These visualizations use the Seaborn package. These are called pairplots, which show the distribution of each variable and their relationships.

def popbudgrev_func(col):
    pop_budg_rev_list = df_movies_clean.columns[1:4]
    sns.pairplot(df_movies_clean[pop_budg_rev_list], hue=col, height=3.5);

ax[0].set_ylabel("Popularity")
ax[0].set_title("Popularity vs Budget")

#Popularity vs Adjusted Budget
ax[1].scatter(x = df_movies_clean['budget_adj'], y = df_movies_clean['popularity'])
ax[1].set_xlabel("Adjusted Budget")
ax[1].set_ylabel("Popularity")
ax[1].set_title("Popularity vs Adjusted Budget")

#Popularity vs Revenue
ax[2].scatter(x = df_movies_clean['revenue'], y=df_movies_clean['popularity'])

ax[2].set_ylabel("Popularity")
ax[2].set_title("Popularity vs Revenue")

#Popularity vs Adjusted Revenue
ax[3].scatter(x=df_movies_clean['revenue_adj'], y=df_movies_clean['popularity'])

ax[3].set_title("Popularity vs Adjusted Revenue")

Both budget and adjusted budget seem to show that movies with budgets between 1M and 2M tend to be be more popular. Let's look at revenue and adjusted revenue next.

The revenue scatterplots don't show a very strong correlation between revenue and popularity. Further investigation is needed. We have added revenue and budget scatterplots with line regressions below.

Now let's look at runtime.

The runtime scatterplot shows that movies between 1 and 3.5 hours tend to be more popular.

Conclusions¶

In this section, we will summarize our findings.

The questions we explored:

  • Are movies with higher budgets more popular?
  • Do more popular movies have higher revenue?
  • Do movies with higher budgets have higher revenue?
  • Are runtime and popularity correlated?
  • Do movies with longer runtimes have higher revenue?
  • Which movies have the highest revenue (top 10)? Who directed them?
  • Which movies are the most popular (top 10)? Who directed them?

Popularity¶

  • The most popular movie is Jurassic World.
  • There doesn't appear to be a correlation between popularity and director, but deeper analysis is needed.
  • Movies with budgets between 1M and 2M seem to be more popular.
  • There doesn't appear to be a correlation between reven and popularity, further investigation is needed.
  • Movies with runtimes between 1 and 3.5 hours appear to be more popular.

Revenue¶

  • The movie with the highest revenue is Avatar.
  • There may be a correlation between certain directors and revenue, as some directors appear more than once in the Top 10 movies with highest revenue.
  • Again, there doesn't appear to be a correlation between popularity and revenue, but deeper analysis is needed.
  • Revenue vs Budget and Adjusted Revenue vs Adjusted Budget show slighty different findings.
  • Revenue vs Budget showed that movies with budgets between 1.5M and 3M had more revenue, however Adjusted Revenue vs Adjusted budget showed that there were several higher revenues with budgets <1M. Further analysis is needed
  • Movies with runtimes between 1 and 3.5 hours appeart to have higher revenue.

Summary¶

This broad overview of the available data gives us the ability to conceptualize the available variables and visualize the possible relationships between them. In a way, it provides a roadmap to further statistical analysis. The disadvantage is that we haven't made concrete, stastical conclusions for decision making. Our analysis is dependent on the limitations of the data provided, given that there were missing and null values. We did not perform deeper stastical calculations and therefore can only make assumptions and not solid conclusions with our analysis.

With our analysis:

We can infer that movies with budgets between 1M and 2M appear to be more popular. Likewise, movies with budgets between 1.5M and 3M appear to earn more revenue. However, with the adjusted values, we find that there are several movies with budgets <1M that do earn more. Further investigation is needed.

Our Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) with directors was inconclusive and requires more investigation as well.

We can also conclude that movies with runtimes between 1 and 3.5 hours tend to be more popular and earn more revenue. We also discovered that most movies fall into this range. Further investigation is needed.

There are many factors that could be explored with more in-depth analysis on this topic, however we now have a good understanding about how popularity, revenue, budget, and runtime influence each other.
